{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_ea626891e41240b7beca89e0","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t.. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/luigi.png\n2\t   :alt: Luigi Logo\n3\t   :align: center\n4\t\n5\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/endpoint.svg?url=https%3A%2F%2Factions-badge.atrox.dev%2Fspotify%2Fluigi%2Fbadge&label=build&logo=none&%3Fref%3Dmaster&style=flat\n6\t    :target: https://actions-badge.atrox.dev/spotify/luigi/goto?ref=master\n7\t\n8\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/codecov/c/github/spotify/luigi/master.svg?style=flat\n9\t    :target: https://codecov.io/gh/spotify/luigi?branch=master\n10\t\n11\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/luigi.svg?style=flat\n12\t   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi\n13\t\n14\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/luigi.svg?style=flat\n15\t   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi\n16\t\n17\t.. image:: https://readthedocs.org/projects/luigi/badge/?version=stable\n18\t    :target: https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/?badge=stable\n19\t    :alt: Documentation Status\n20\t\n21\tLuigi is a Python (3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13 tested) package that helps you build complex\n22\tpipelines of batch jobs. It handles dependency resolution, workflow management,\n23\tvisualization, handling failures, command line integration, and much more.\n24\t\n25\tGetting Started\n26\t---------------\n27\t\n28\tRun ``pip install luigi`` to install the latest stable version from `PyPI\n29\t<https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi>`_. `Documentation for the latest release\n30\t<https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/>`__ is hosted on readthedocs.\n31\t\n32\tRun ``pip install luigi[toml]`` to install Luigi with `TOML-based configs\n33\t<https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/configuration.html>`__ support.\n34\t\n35\tFor the bleeding edge code, ``pip install\n36\tgit+https://github.com/spotify/luigi.git``. `Bleeding edge documentation\n37\t<https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/>`__ is also available.\n38\t\n39\tBackground\n40\t----------\n41\t\n42\tThe purpose of Luigi is to address all the plumbing typically associated\n43\twith long-running batch processes. You want to chain many tasks,\n44\tautomate them, and failures *will* happen. These tasks can be anything,\n45\tbut are typically long running things like\n46\t`Hadoop <http://hadoop.apache.org/>`_ jobs, dumping data to/from\n47\tdatabases, running machine learning algorithms, or anything else.\n48\t\n49\tThere are other software packages that focus on lower level aspects of\n50\tdata processing, like `Hive <http://hive.apache.org/>`__,\n51\t`Pig <http://pig.apache.org/>`_, or\n52\t`Cascading <http://www.cascading.org/>`_. Luigi is not a framework to\n53\treplace these. Instead it helps you stitch many tasks together, where\n54\teach task can be a `Hive query <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hive.html>`__,\n55\ta `Hadoop job in Java <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hadoop_jar.html>`_,\n56\ta  `Spark job in Scala or Python <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.spark.html>`_,\n57\ta Python snippet,\n58\t`dumping a table <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.sqla.html>`_\n59\tfrom a database, or anything else. It's easy to build up\n60\tlong-running pipelines that comprise thousands of tasks and take days or\n61\tweeks to complete. Luigi takes care of a lot of the workflow management\n62\tso that you can focus on the tasks themselves and their dependencies.\n63\t\n64\tYou can build pretty much any task you want, but Luigi also comes with a\n65\t*toolbox* of several common task templates that you use. It includes\n66\tsupport for running\n67\t`Python mapreduce jobs <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hadoop.html>`_\n68\tin Hadoop, as well as\n69\t`Hive <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hive.html>`__,\n70\tand `Pig <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.pig.html>`__,\n71\tjobs. It also comes with\n72\t`file system abstractions for HDFS <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hdfs.html>`_,\n73\tand local files that ensures all file system operations are atomic. This\n74\tis important because it means your data pipeline will not crash in a\n75\tstate containing partial data.\n76\t\n77\tVisualiser page\n78\t---------------\n79\t\n80\tThe Luigi server comes with a web interface too, so you can search and filter\n81\tamong all your tasks.\n82\t\n83\t.. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/visualiser_front_page.png\n84\t   :alt: Visualiser page\n85\t\n86\tDependency graph example\n87\t------------------------\n88\t\n89\tJust to give you an idea of what Luigi does, this is a screen shot from\n90\tsomething we are running in production. Using Luigi's visualiser, we get\n91\ta nice visual overview of the dependency graph of the workflow. Each\n92\tnode represents a task which has to be run. Green tasks are already\n93\tcompleted whereas yellow tasks are yet to be run. Most of these tasks\n94\tare Hadoop jobs, but there are also some things that run locally and\n95\tbuild up data files.\n96\t\n97\t.. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/user_recs.png\n98\t   :alt: Dependency graph\n99\t\n100\tPhilosophy\n101\t----------\n102\t\n103\tConceptually, Luigi is similar to `GNU\n104\tMake <http://www.gnu.org/software/make/>`_ where you have certain tasks\n105\tand these tasks in turn may have dependencies on other tasks. There are\n106\talso some similarities to `Oozie <http://oozie.apache.org/>`_\n107\tand `Azkaban <https://azkaban.github.io/>`_. One major\n108\tdifference is that Luigi is not just built specifically for Hadoop, and\n109\tit's easy to extend it with other kinds of tasks.\n110\t\n111\tEverything in Luigi is in Python. Instead of XML configuration or\n112\tsimilar external data files, the dependency graph is specified *within\n113\tPython*. This makes it easy to build up complex dependency graphs of\n114\ttasks, where the dependencies can involve date algebra or recursive\n115\treferences to other versions of the same task. However, the workflow can\n116\ttrigger things not in Python, such as running\n117\t`Pig scripts <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.pig.html>`_\n118\tor `scp'ing files <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.ssh.html>`_.\n119\t\n120\tWho uses Luigi?\n121\t---------------\n122\t\n123\tWe use Luigi internally at `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_ to run\n124\tthousands of tasks every day, organized in complex dependency graphs.\n125\tMost of these tasks are Hadoop jobs. Luigi provides an infrastructure\n126\tthat powers all kinds of stuff including recommendations, toplists, A/B\n127\ttest analysis, external reports, internal dashboards, etc.\n128\t\n129\tSince Luigi is open source and without any registration walls, the exact number\n130\tof Luigi users is unknown. But based on the number of unique contributors, we\n131\texpect hundreds of enterprises to use it. Some users have written blog posts\n132\tor held presentations about Luigi:\n133\t\n134\t* `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_ `(presentation, 2014) <http://www.slideshare.net/erikbern/luigi-presentation-nyc-data-science>`__\n135\t* `Foursquare <https://foursquare.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2013) <http://www.slideshare.net/OpenAnayticsMeetup/luigi-presentation-17-23199897>`__\n136\t* `Mortar Data (Datadog) <https://www.datadoghq.com/>`_ `(documentation / tutorial) <http://help.mortardata.com/technologies/luigi>`__\n137\t* `Stripe <https://stripe.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2014) <http://www.slideshare.net/PyData/python-as-part-of-a-production-machine-learning-stack-by-michael-manapat-pydata-sv-2014>`__\n138\t* `Buffer <https://buffer.com/>`_ `(blog, 2014) <https://buffer.com/resources/buffers-new-data-architecture/>`__\n139\t* `SeatGeek <https://seatgeek.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://chairnerd.seatgeek.com/building-out-the-seatgeek-data-pipeline/>`__\n140\t* `Treasure Data <https://www.treasuredata.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://blog.treasuredata.com/blog/2015/02/25/managing-the-data-pipeline-with-git-luigi/>`__\n141\t* `Growth Intelligence <http://growthintel.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2015) <http://www.slideshare.net/growthintel/a-beginners-guide-to-building-data-pipelines-with-luigi>`__\n142\t* `AdRoll <https://www.adroll.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://tech.adroll.com/blog/data/2015/09/22/data-pipelines-docker.html>`__\n143\t* 17zuoye `(presentation, 2015) <https://speakerdeck.com/mvj3/luiti-an-offline-task-management-framework>`__\n144\t* `Custobar <https://www.custobar.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2016) <http://www.slideshare.net/teemukurppa/managing-data-workflows-with-luigi>`__\n145\t* `Blendle <https://launch.blendle.com/>`_ `(presentation) <http://www.anneschuth.nl/wp-content/uploads/sea-anneschuth-streamingblendle.pdf#page=126>`__\n146\t* `TrustYou <http://www.trustyou.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2015) <https://speakerdeck.com/mfcabrera/pydata-berlin-2015-processing-hotel-reviews-with-python>`__\n147\t* `Groupon <https://www.groupon.com/>`_ / `OrderUp <https://orderup.com>`_ `(alternative implementation) <https://github.com/groupon/luigi-warehouse>`__\n148\t* `Red Hat - Marketing Operations <https://www.redhat.com>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://github.com/rh-marketingops/rh-mo-scc-luigi>`__\n149\t* `GetNinjas <https://www.getninjas.com.br/>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://labs.getninjas.com.br/using-luigi-to-create-and-monitor-pipelines-of-batch-jobs-eb8b3cd2a574>`__\n150\t* `voyages-sncf.com <https://www.voyages-sncf.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2017) <https://github.com/voyages-sncf-technologies/meetup-afpy-nantes-luigi>`__\n151\t* `Open Targets <https://www.opentargets.org/>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://blog.opentargets.org/using-containers-with-luigi>`__\n152\t* `Leipzig University Library <https://ub.uni-leipzig.de>`_ `(presentation, 2016) <https://de.slideshare.net/MartinCzygan/build-your-own-discovery-index-of-scholary-eresources>`__ / `(project) <https://finc.info/de/datenquellen>`__\n153\t* `Synetiq <https://synetiq.net/>`_ `(presentation, 2017) <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M4xUQXogSfo>`__\n154\t* `Glossier <https://www.glossier.com/>`_ `(blog, 2018) <https://medium.com/glossier/how-to-build-a-data-warehouse-what-weve-learned-so-far-at-glossier-6ff1e1783e31>`__\n155\t* `Data Revenue <https://www.datarevenue.com/>`_ `(blog, 2018) <https://www.datarevenue.com/en/blog/how-to-scale-your-machine-learning-pipeline>`_\n156\t* `Uppsala University <http://pharmb.io>`_ `(tutorial) <http://uppnex.se/twiki/do/view/Courses/EinfraMPS2015/Luigi.html>`_   / `(presentation, 2015) <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f26PqSXZdWM>`_ / `(slides, 2015) <https://www.slideshare.net/SamuelLampa/building-workflows-with-spotifys-luigi>`_ / `(poster, 2015) <https://pharmb.io/poster/2015-sciluigi/>`_ / `(paper, 2016) <https://doi.org/10.1186/s13321-016-0179-6>`_ / `(project) <https://github.com/pharmbio/sciluigi>`_\n157\t* `GIPHY <https://giphy.com/>`_ `(blog, 2019) <https://engineering.giphy.com/luigi-the-10x-plumber-containerizing-scaling-luigi-in-kubernetes/>`__\n158\t* `xtream <https://xtreamers.io/>`__ `(blog, 2019) <https://towardsdatascience.com/lessons-from-a-real-machine-learning-project-part-1-from-jupyter-to-luigi-bdfd0b050ca5>`__\n159\t* `CIAN <https://cian.ru/>`__ `(presentation, 2019) <https://www.highload.ru/moscow/2019/abstracts/6030>`__\n160\t\n161\tSome more companies are using Luigi but haven't had a chance yet to write about it:\n162\t\n163\t* `Schibsted <http://www.schibsted.com/>`_\n164\t* `enbrite.ly <http://enbrite.ly/>`_\n165\t* `Dow Jones / The Wall Street Journal <http://wsj.com>`_\n166\t* `Hotels.com <https://hotels.com>`_\n167\t* `Newsela <https://newsela.com>`_\n168\t* `Squarespace <https://www.squarespace.com/>`_\n169\t* `OAO <https://adops.com/>`_\n170\t* `Grovo <https://grovo.com/>`_\n171\t* `Weebly <https://www.weebly.com/>`_\n172\t* `Deloitte <https://www.Deloitte.co.uk/>`_\n173\t* `Stacktome <https://stacktome.com/>`_\n174\t* `LINX+Neemu+Chaordic <https://www.chaordic.com.br/>`_\n175\t* `Foxberry <https://www.foxberry.com/>`_\n176\t* `Okko <https://okko.tv/>`_\n177\t* `ISVWorld <http://isvworld.com/>`_\n178\t* `Big Data <https://bigdata.com.br/>`_\n179\t* `Movio <https://movio.co.nz/>`_\n180\t* `Bonnier News <https://www.bonniernews.se/>`_\n181\t* `Starsky Robotics <https://www.starsky.io/>`_\n182\t* `BaseTIS <https://www.basetis.com/>`_\n183\t* `Hopper <https://www.hopper.com/>`_\n184\t* `VOYAGE GROUP/Zucks <https://zucks.co.jp/en/>`_\n185\t* `Textpert <https://www.textpert.ai/>`_\n186\t* `Tracktics <https://www.tracktics.com/>`_\n187\t* `Whizar <https://www.whizar.com/>`_\n188\t* `xtream <https://www.xtreamers.io/>`__\n189\t* `Skyscanner <https://www.skyscanner.net/>`_\n190\t* `Jodel <https://www.jodel.com/>`_\n191\t* `Mekar <https://mekar.id/en/>`_\n192\t* `M3 <https://corporate.m3.com/en/>`_\n193\t* `Assist Digital <https://www.assistdigital.com/>`_\n194\t* `Meltwater <https://www.meltwater.com/>`_\n195\t* `DevSamurai <https://www.devsamurai.com/>`_\n196\t* `Veridas <https://veridas.com/>`_\n197\t* `Aidentified <https://www.aidentified.com/>`_\n198\t\n199\tWe're more than happy to have your company added here. Just send a PR on GitHub.\n200\t\n201\tExternal links\n202\t--------------\n203\t\n204\t* `Mailing List <https://groups.google.com/d/forum/luigi-user/>`_ for discussions and asking questions. (Google Groups)\n205\t* `Releases <https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi>`_ (PyPI)\n206\t* `Source code <https://github.com/spotify/luigi>`_ (GitHub)\n207\t* `Hubot Integration <https://github.com/houzz/hubot-luigi>`_ plugin for Slack, Hipchat, etc (GitHub)\n208\t\n209\tAuthors\n210\t-------\n211\t\n212\tLuigi was built at `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_, mainly by\n213\t`Erik Bernhardsson <https://github.com/erikbern>`_ and\n214\t`Elias Freider <https://github.com/freider>`_.\n215\t`Many other people <https://github.com/spotify/luigi/graphs/contributors>`_\n216\thave contributed since open sourcing in late 2012.\n217\t`Arash Rouhani <https://github.com/tarrasch>`_ was the chief maintainer from 2015 to 2019, and now\n218\tSpotify's Data Team maintains Luigi.\n219\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5ce3aeda-9c9d-4e2b-a71f-2b15a2883016","uuid":"d324d103-a829-4c80-95b2-b8fe339c0411","timestamp":"2026-04-06T10:13:45.470Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst","content":".. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/luigi.png\n   :alt: Luigi Logo\n   :align: center\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/endpoint.svg?url=https%3A%2F%2Factions-badge.atrox.dev%2Fspotify%2Fluigi%2Fbadge&label=build&logo=none&%3Fref%3Dmaster&style=flat\n    :target: https://actions-badge.atrox.dev/spotify/luigi/goto?ref=master\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/codecov/c/github/spotify/luigi/master.svg?style=flat\n    :target: https://codecov.io/gh/spotify/luigi?branch=master\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/luigi.svg?style=flat\n   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/luigi.svg?style=flat\n   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi\n\n.. image:: https://readthedocs.org/projects/luigi/badge/?version=stable\n    :target: https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/?badge=stable\n    :alt: Documentation Status\n\nLuigi is a Python (3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13 tested) package that helps you build complex\npipelines of batch jobs. It handles dependency resolution, workflow management,\nvisualization, handling failures, command line integration, and much more.\n\nGetting Started\n---------------\n\nRun ``pip install luigi`` to install the latest stable version from `PyPI\n<https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi>`_. `Documentation for the latest release\n<https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/>`__ is hosted on readthedocs.\n\nRun ``pip install luigi[toml]`` to install Luigi with `TOML-based configs\n<https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/configuration.html>`__ support.\n\nFor the bleeding edge code, ``pip install\ngit+https://github.com/spotify/luigi.git``. `Bleeding edge documentation\n<https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/>`__ is also available.\n\nBackground\n----------\n\nThe purpose of Luigi is to address all the plumbing typically associated\nwith long-running batch processes. You want to chain many tasks,\nautomate them, and failures *will* happen. These tasks can be anything,\nbut are typically long running things like\n`Hadoop <http://hadoop.apache.org/>`_ jobs, dumping data to/from\ndatabases, running machine learning algorithms, or anything else.\n\nThere are other software packages that focus on lower level aspects of\ndata processing, like `Hive <http://hive.apache.org/>`__,\n`Pig <http://pig.apache.org/>`_, or\n`Cascading <http://www.cascading.org/>`_. Luigi is not a framework to\nreplace these. Instead it helps you stitch many tasks together, where\neach task can be a `Hive query <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hive.html>`__,\na `Hadoop job in Java <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hadoop_jar.html>`_,\na  `Spark job in Scala or Python <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.spark.html>`_,\na Python snippet,\n`dumping a table <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.sqla.html>`_\nfrom a database, or anything else. It's easy to build up\nlong-running pipelines that comprise thousands of tasks and take days or\nweeks to complete. Luigi takes care of a lot of the workflow management\nso that you can focus on the tasks themselves and their dependencies.\n\nYou can build pretty much any task you want, but Luigi also comes with a\n*toolbox* of several common task templates that you use. It includes\nsupport for running\n`Python mapreduce jobs <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hadoop.html>`_\nin Hadoop, as well as\n`Hive <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hive.html>`__,\nand `Pig <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.pig.html>`__,\njobs. It also comes with\n`file system abstractions for HDFS <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hdfs.html>`_,\nand local files that ensures all file system operations are atomic. This\nis important because it means your data pipeline will not crash in a\nstate containing partial data.\n\nVisualiser page\n---------------\n\nThe Luigi server comes with a web interface too, so you can search and filter\namong all your tasks.\n\n.. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/visualiser_front_page.png\n   :alt: Visualiser page\n\nDependency graph example\n------------------------\n\nJust to give you an idea of what Luigi does, this is a screen shot from\nsomething we are running in production. Using Luigi's visualiser, we get\na nice visual overview of the dependency graph of the workflow. Each\nnode represents a task which has to be run. Green tasks are already\ncompleted whereas yellow tasks are yet to be run. Most of these tasks\nare Hadoop jobs, but there are also some things that run locally and\nbuild up data files.\n\n.. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/user_recs.png\n   :alt: Dependency graph\n\nPhilosophy\n----------\n\nConceptually, Luigi is similar to `GNU\nMake <http://www.gnu.org/software/make/>`_ where you have certain tasks\nand these tasks in turn may have dependencies on other tasks. There are\nalso some similarities to `Oozie <http://oozie.apache.org/>`_\nand `Azkaban <https://azkaban.github.io/>`_. One major\ndifference is that Luigi is not just built specifically for Hadoop, and\nit's easy to extend it with other kinds of tasks.\n\nEverything in Luigi is in Python. Instead of XML configuration or\nsimilar external data files, the dependency graph is specified *within\nPython*. This makes it easy to build up complex dependency graphs of\ntasks, where the dependencies can involve date algebra or recursive\nreferences to other versions of the same task. However, the workflow can\ntrigger things not in Python, such as running\n`Pig scripts <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.pig.html>`_\nor `scp'ing files <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.ssh.html>`_.\n\nWho uses Luigi?\n---------------\n\nWe use Luigi internally at `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_ to run\nthousands of tasks every day, organized in complex dependency graphs.\nMost of these tasks are Hadoop jobs. Luigi provides an infrastructure\nthat powers all kinds of stuff including recommendations, toplists, A/B\ntest analysis, external reports, internal dashboards, etc.\n\nSince Luigi is open source and without any registration walls, the exact number\nof Luigi users is unknown. But based on the number of unique contributors, we\nexpect hundreds of enterprises to use it. Some users have written blog posts\nor held presentations about Luigi:\n\n* `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_ `(presentation, 2014) <http://www.slideshare.net/erikbern/luigi-presentation-nyc-data-science>`__\n* `Foursquare <https://foursquare.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2013) <http://www.slideshare.net/OpenAnayticsMeetup/luigi-presentation-17-23199897>`__\n* `Mortar Data (Datadog) <https://www.datadoghq.com/>`_ `(documentation / tutorial) <http://help.mortardata.com/technologies/luigi>`__\n* `Stripe <https://stripe.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2014) <http://www.slideshare.net/PyData/python-as-part-of-a-production-machine-learning-stack-by-michael-manapat-pydata-sv-2014>`__\n* `Buffer <https://buffer.com/>`_ `(blog, 2014) <https://buffer.com/resources/buffers-new-data-architecture/>`__\n* `SeatGeek <https://seatgeek.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://chairnerd.seatgeek.com/building-out-the-seatgeek-data-pipeline/>`__\n* `Treasure Data <https://www.treasuredata.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://blog.treasuredata.com/blog/2015/02/25/managing-the-data-pipeline-with-git-luigi/>`__\n* `Growth Intelligence <http://growthintel.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2015) <http://www.slideshare.net/growthintel/a-beginners-guide-to-building-data-pipelines-with-luigi>`__\n* `AdRoll <https://www.adroll.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://tech.adroll.com/blog/data/2015/09/22/data-pipelines-docker.html>`__\n* 17zuoye `(presentation, 2015) <https://speakerdeck.com/mvj3/luiti-an-offline-task-management-framework>`__\n* `Custobar <https://www.custobar.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2016) <http://www.slideshare.net/teemukurppa/managing-data-workflows-with-luigi>`__\n* `Blendle <https://launch.blendle.com/>`_ `(presentation) <http://www.anneschuth.nl/wp-content/uploads/sea-anneschuth-streamingblendle.pdf#page=126>`__\n* `TrustYou <http://www.trustyou.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2015) <https://speakerdeck.com/mfcabrera/pydata-berlin-2015-processing-hotel-reviews-with-python>`__\n* `Groupon <https://www.groupon.com/>`_ / `OrderUp <https://orderup.com>`_ `(alternative implementation) <https://github.com/groupon/luigi-warehouse>`__\n* `Red Hat - Marketing Operations <https://www.redhat.com>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://github.com/rh-marketingops/rh-mo-scc-luigi>`__\n* `GetNinjas <https://www.getninjas.com.br/>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://labs.getninjas.com.br/using-luigi-to-create-and-monitor-pipelines-of-batch-jobs-eb8b3cd2a574>`__\n* `voyages-sncf.com <https://www.voyages-sncf.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2017) <https://github.com/voyages-sncf-technologies/meetup-afpy-nantes-luigi>`__\n* `Open Targets <https://www.opentargets.org/>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://blog.opentargets.org/using-containers-with-luigi>`__\n* `Leipzig University Library <https://ub.uni-leipzig.de>`_ `(presentation, 2016) <https://de.slideshare.net/MartinCzygan/build-your-own-discovery-index-of-scholary-eresources>`__ / `(project) <https://finc.info/de/datenquellen>`__\n* `Synetiq <https://synetiq.net/>`_ `(presentation, 2017) <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M4xUQXogSfo>`__\n* `Glossier <https://www.glossier.com/>`_ `(blog, 2018) <https://medium.com/glossier/how-to-build-a-data-warehouse-what-weve-learned-so-far-at-glossier-6ff1e1783e31>`__\n* `Data Revenue <https://www.datarevenue.com/>`_ `(blog, 2018) <https://www.datarevenue.com/en/blog/how-to-scale-your-machine-learning-pipeline>`_\n* `Uppsala University <http://pharmb.io>`_ `(tutorial) <http://uppnex.se/twiki/do/view/Courses/EinfraMPS2015/Luigi.html>`_   / `(presentation, 2015) <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f26PqSXZdWM>`_ / `(slides, 2015) <https://www.slideshare.net/SamuelLampa/building-workflows-with-spotifys-luigi>`_ / `(poster, 2015) <https://pharmb.io/poster/2015-sciluigi/>`_ / `(paper, 2016) <https://doi.org/10.1186/s13321-016-0179-6>`_ / `(project) <https://github.com/pharmbio/sciluigi>`_\n* `GIPHY <https://giphy.com/>`_ `(blog, 2019) <https://engineering.giphy.com/luigi-the-10x-plumber-containerizing-scaling-luigi-in-kubernetes/>`__\n* `xtream <https://xtreamers.io/>`__ `(blog, 2019) <https://towardsdatascience.com/lessons-from-a-real-machine-learning-project-part-1-from-jupyter-to-luigi-bdfd0b050ca5>`__\n* `CIAN <https://cian.ru/>`__ `(presentation, 2019) <https://www.highload.ru/moscow/2019/abstracts/6030>`__\n\nSome more companies are using Luigi but haven't had a chance yet to write about it:\n\n* `Schibsted <http://www.schibsted.com/>`_\n* `enbrite.ly <http://enbrite.ly/>`_\n* `Dow Jones / The Wall Street Journal <http://wsj.com>`_\n* `Hotels.com <https://hotels.com>`_\n* `Newsela <https://newsela.com>`_\n* `Squarespace <https://www.squarespace.com/>`_\n* `OAO <https://adops.com/>`_\n* `Grovo <https://grovo.com/>`_\n* `Weebly <https://www.weebly.com/>`_\n* `Deloitte <https://www.Deloitte.co.uk/>`_\n* `Stacktome <https://stacktome.com/>`_\n* `LINX+Neemu+Chaordic <https://www.chaordic.com.br/>`_\n* `Foxberry <https://www.foxberry.com/>`_\n* `Okko <https://okko.tv/>`_\n* `ISVWorld <http://isvworld.com/>`_\n* `Big Data <https://bigdata.com.br/>`_\n* `Movio <https://movio.co.nz/>`_\n* `Bonnier News <https://www.bonniernews.se/>`_\n* `Starsky Robotics <https://www.starsky.io/>`_\n* `BaseTIS <https://www.basetis.com/>`_\n* `Hopper <https://www.hopper.com/>`_\n* `VOYAGE GROUP/Zucks <https://zucks.co.jp/en/>`_\n* `Textpert <https://www.textpert.ai/>`_\n* `Tracktics <https://www.tracktics.com/>`_\n* `Whizar <https://www.whizar.com/>`_\n* `xtream <https://www.xtreamers.io/>`__\n* `Skyscanner <https://www.skyscanner.net/>`_\n* `Jodel <https://www.jodel.com/>`_\n* `Mekar <https://mekar.id/en/>`_\n* `M3 <https://corporate.m3.com/en/>`_\n* `Assist Digital <https://www.assistdigital.com/>`_\n* `Meltwater <https://www.meltwater.com/>`_\n* `DevSamurai <https://www.devsamurai.com/>`_\n* `Veridas <https://veridas.com/>`_\n* `Aidentified <https://www.aidentified.com/>`_\n\nWe're more than happy to have your company added here. Just send a PR on GitHub.\n\nExternal links\n--------------\n\n* `Mailing List <https://groups.google.com/d/forum/luigi-user/>`_ for discussions and asking questions. (Google Groups)\n* `Releases <https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi>`_ (PyPI)\n* `Source code <https://github.com/spotify/luigi>`_ (GitHub)\n* `Hubot Integration <https://github.com/houzz/hubot-luigi>`_ plugin for Slack, Hipchat, etc (GitHub)\n\nAuthors\n-------\n\nLuigi was built at `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_, mainly by\n`Erik Bernhardsson <https://github.com/erikbern>`_ and\n`Elias Freider <https://github.com/freider>`_.\n`Many other people <https://github.com/spotify/luigi/graphs/contributors>`_\nhave contributed since open sourcing in late 2012.\n`Arash Rouhani <https://github.com/tarrasch>`_ was the chief maintainer from 2015 to 2019, and now\nSpotify's Data Team maintains Luigi.\n","numLines":219,"startLine":1,"totalLines":219}}}
